# API controllers (MoneyManager.API)

## Role

Controllers translate HTTP to MediatR commands/queries and map handler results to `IActionResult`. **No business logic** (validation that belongs in handlers/validators, authorization decisions beyond attributes, orchestration).

## Conventions

- `[ApiController]` and explicit `[Route("api/…")]` in kebab-case (e.g. `api/expenses`, `api/payment-methods`).
- Inject **`IMediator`** via constructor (all current controllers use this pattern).
- Include **`CancellationToken cancellationToken`** on actions and pass it to `_mediator.Send(…, cancellationToken)`.
- Dispatch with `_mediator.Send(new SomeCommand(…), cancellationToken)` or `_mediator.Send(new SomeQuery(…), cancellationToken)`.
- Map results with **`ApiResults.*`** helpers or direct `Ok` / `CreatedAtAction` / `NoContent` for success paths (see `MoneyManager.API.Infrastructure.ApiResults`).

```csharp
var result = await _mediator.Send(new UpdateExpenseCommand(id, userId, model), cancellationToken);
if (result.IsSuccess) return Ok(result.Updated);
if (result.IsConflict) return ApiResults.Conflict("The expense was modified by another request.", result.ConflictCurrent);
return ApiResults.NotFound("Expense not found.");
```

## Auth

- `[Authorize(AuthenticationSchemes = AuthSchemes.Microsoft)]` on controllers (fallback policy also requires authenticated user).
- **User-scoped endpoints:** add `[RequireUserId]` on the controller; get `Guid userId` from `UserIdHttpContext.GetRequired(HttpContext)` and pass into commands/queries.
- **Global endpoints:** omit `[RequireUserId]` (e.g. categories, payment methods); add an XML summary comment explaining the resource is shared across users.
- Do not parse JWT claims in controllers; `IResolveUserId` / `RequireUserIdFilter` handle identity resolution.

## ApiResults Helpers

| Helper | Status | Use when |
|--------|--------|----------|
| `ValidationError(string)` | 400 | Single validation message from handler result |
| `ValidationError(IDictionary<…>)` | 400 | Field-level errors |
| `NotFound(string)` | 404 | Entity not found |
| `Conflict(string, extensions?)` | 409 | Optimistic concurrency conflict |
| `Unauthorized(string)` | 401 | Identity not resolved |
| `UnexpectedFailure(string?)` | 500 | Unexpected null / failure with no specific status |

## Controller Pre-Processing

Some HTTP concerns stay in the controller when they are transport-specific (not business logic):

- **JSON patch parsing:** `ExpensePatchParser.Parse(jsonElement)` in `PatchExpense` before sending `PatchExpenseCommand`.
- **Bulk request shaping:** map `BulkUpdateRequest` fields to `ExpenseFieldNames` dictionary before sending command.

Keep orchestration and business rules in handlers/repositories.

## Middleware Pipeline

Order in `Program.cs`: exception handler → Swagger (dev) → CORS → `RequestLoggingMiddleware` → authentication → authorization → `MapDefaultEndpoints` → `MapControllers`.
